<div>		



<span class="section_title">2005 International CES(r) TechZones Highlight Consumer VoIP, Digital Imaging and Wireless</span>

	<br><br>
	<span class="subhead">Innovations Plus Debut Features Hot New Technologies and Trends</span>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>New York, New York&nbsp;-&nbsp;11/10/2004</i></strong>
<br><br>
2005 International CES attendees will get an exclusive view of some of the hottest 

technologies and trends including home recording technologies, VoIP, wireless and digital imaging at more than 20 TechZones 

located throughout the show floor.  CES TechZones bring together products and technologies from a variety of exhibitors to 

spotlight emerging trends and the latest technologies generating excitement within consumer electronics.   The 2005 

International CES, the world's largest annual technology showcase, will be held in Las Vegas, Nev., from January 6-9, 

2005.<P>  

Seventeen of the TechZones will be located in the new CES Central and South Plazas, with the highest concentration located in 

Innovations Plus in the CES Central Plaza outside the Las Vegas Convention Center.  Tech Zones in this area include those 

focusing on Bluetooth, Cardio Play, RFID, Studio@Home and TechHome.  In addition to housing the Tech Zones, Innovations Plus 

also features the 2005 International CES Innovations honorees displays. <P>

"TechZones offer a compelling display of new trends and technologies within consumer electronics, showcasing the breadth and 

depth of our amazing industry" said Karen Chupka, vice president of events and conferences for the Consumer Electronics 

Association (CEA), producer of CES.  "They provide a great way for our attendees to see the next wave of 'latest and 

greatest' all within one area.  By showcasing these TechZones along with the popular Innovations honoree displays, 

Innovations Plus is poised to be a 'must attend' venue for experiencing some of the world's premiere products and 

technologies," stated Chupka. <P>

Whether attendees are seeking information on mobile electronics, home entertainment and networking or digital imaging and 

production, all visitors to the 2005 International CES TechZones are guaranteed to experience an enlightening showcase of hot 

new products and trends.  A sample of these TechZones include: <P>

Cardio Play Zone<BR>
Fitness today means high-intensity fitness products.  Technologies can help entertain us while we experience a maximum cardio 

workout.  The products in this TechZone count calories burned, help increase/decrease intensity levels, feature videos or 

play music.<BR><BR>

Connected Home Entertainment<BR>
See the most innovative, hard-wired, professionally installed systems for whole-house audio and video, including new 

multi-room networked entertainment.<BR><BR>

Consumer VoIp, Sponsored by pulver.com<BR>
With IP-enabled devices shifting from telecom service to information service, pulver.com is showcasing the next generation of 

IP-enabled devices and the new service providers for them. This program, along with pulver.com's Consumer VoIP Summit, will 

be presented for the first time at the 2005 International CES.  <BR><BR>

Digital Car/Telematics <BR>
Test the products that make travel easier and more enjoyable, including the most innovative digital car products. See them at 

the International CES, the world's largest mobile electronics event.<BR><BR>

Flash Forward 2.0:  Bringing Digital Imaging Into Focus<BR>
Returning to the International CES, Flash Forward 2.0 Bringing Digital Imaging Into Focus is an exclusive digital imaging 

showcase, featuring the hottest advances and applications in every aspect of digital imaging.  The InfoTrends Cap Ventures 

ImageScape press event, sponsored by Kodak, will be located within this TechZone.<BR><BR>

MBOA Ultrawideband<BR>
Wireless continues to flourish at the 2005 International CES.  Wireless connectivity has enabled a new mobile lifestyle 

filled with conveniences for mobile computing users at work and home.  Learn more about the Ultrawideband solutions for 

bandwidth, cost, power consumption and physical size requirements of next-generation consumer electronics devices.<BR><BR>

RFID<BR>
Used by some of the largest retailers such as Target and WalMart, radio frequency (RF) tags are the barcode of the future.  

RF technology enables the tracking of consumer electronics with an RF chip to determine its locations, delivering remote 

information about the product.<BR><BR>

Studio@Home & HD Pro Showcase<BR>
The International CES is the premiere tradeshow for home technology and entertainment.  Produced in cooperation with CMP 

Information, Studio@Home includes the latest home recording and editing products, electronic music software, DJ equipment, 

keyboards and more.  Co-sponsored by CMP Information, HD Pro Showcase highlights the latest advances in high definition 

television production and broadcast technologies.<P>

For a complete list of TechZones, please visit www.cesweb.org/techzones.  For more news on CES before, during and after the 

show, go to www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<P>
Note to Journalists:  Journalists are encouraged to arrive in Las Vegas by Tuesday, January 4, 2005 to take advantage of all 

the CES press conferences and events.  CES Unveiled: The Official Press Event of the International CES will run January 4 

from 4:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m. in the Las Vegas Convention Center, room S226, across the hallway from the CES Press Room.  A 

list of press room hours and services is posted at www.CESweb.org.
<P>
About CEA:<BR>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) is the preeminent trade association promoting growth in the consumer technology 

industry through technology policy, events, research, promotion and the fostering of business and strategic relationships.  

CEA represents more than 1,750 corporate members involved in the design, development, manufacturing, distribution and 

integration of audio, video, mobile electronics, wireless and landline communications, information technology, home 

networking, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services that are sold through consumer channels. Combined, 

CEA's members account for more than $90 billion in annual sales.  CEA's resources are available online at www.CE.org, the 

definitive source for information about the consumer electronics industry.<BR>
CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Defining Tomorrow's Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested 

into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, 

market research and legislative advocacy.

UPCOMING EVENTS<BR><BR>
